Introduction¶

This report is an exploration of data on countries around the world. Gapminder World has collected a variety of data on how people live their lives across the globe. This report will try to identify trends in the following datasets for the United States:

  • Life expectancy - The average number of years a newborn child would live if current mortality rates stayed the same
  • Happiness score (WHR) - Measured using the Cantril life ladder which is explained below
  • The income per person- GDP/capita with inflation adjusted to 2011 Purchasing Power Parity (PPP)
  • The unemployment rate for individuals 15 years and over
  • Working hours per week - Calucualted by the total amount of yearly working hours divided by 52 weeks

Cantril Life Ladder Method¶

It is the national average response to the question of life evaluations asking the following question: "Please imagine a ladder, with steps numbered from 0 at the bottom to 10 at the top. The top of the ladder represents the best possible life for you and the bottom of the ladder represents the worst life for you. On which stepof the ladder would you say you personally feel you stand at this time?" The dataset expresses the answers as a percentage

The questions to explore are as follows:¶

  1. Does a higher income lead to a higher life expectancy?
  2. Does a higher unemployment rate lead to a lower life expectancy?
  3. Does a higher hours worked per week lead to a higher life expectancy?
  4. Does a higher hours worked per week lead to a happier nation?
  5. Does a higher income mean a nation is more happy?
  6. Does a higher unemployment rate mean a nation is less happy?

We can see that this data has data that goes up to the year 2100. Since we are only interested in data up to the year 2019, the data for years beyond that will be trimmed off. From the df.shape we can see that we have 302 columns, and the last column is the year 2100, which is 81 years more than we need. So we will select the desired columns by doing 302-81 which equals 221. we will plug this into our .iloc function

1. Does a higher income lead to a higher life expectancy?¶

To explore this lets see how a scatter plot of life expectancy and income compare. Our data for US life expectancy and US income both have data from date ranges of 1800 to 2019 so no further trimming will be required!

In [219]:
plt.scatter(us_life_exp, us_income)
plt.title(' US Life Expectancy Vs US Income')
plt.xlabel('US Life Expectancy')
plt.ylabel('US Income')
plt.show()

We can see a strong positive correlation that as time goes on, we can tentativley say that a higher income in the United States can potentially mean a higher life expectancy

2. Does a higher unemployment rate lead to a lower life expectancy?¶

Our data for US unemployment ranges from 1947 to 2017 so we will trim our life expectancy data to match. Our life expectancy data is from dates ranging 1800 to 2019

1947 - 1800 = 147

In [220]:
us_life_exp

Conclusion¶

Does a higher income lead to a higher life expectancy?¶

We can see a strong positive correlation between higher income and higher life expectancy. However, since this study has not performed any inferential statistics we cannot say for sure that a higher income leads to a higher life expectancy.

Does a higher unemployment rate lead to a lower life expectancy?¶

The charts created show a weak positive correlation but also show that towards the right side a little above 78 years old we see unemployment numbers of all ranges. The average, combined genders, US life expectancy in 2017, which is the range for the data used was 78.6 according to the CDC. No significant correlation can be determined.

Does a higher hours worked per week lead to a higher life expectancy?¶

During the late 1990's we can see a significant drop in working hours. And after that change happened, life expectancy did go go up. However we cannot say for certain that this increase in life expectancy is due to shortened work hours. It would be interesting to look further into but this is beyond the scope of this study.

Does a higher hours worked per week lead to a happier nation?¶

No correlation is observed

Does a higher income mean a nation is more happy?¶

We can see a slighlty negative correlation. This implies that a slightly lower income means more happiness. However we cannot say for certain that higher happiness score is a direct causation lower income. There could be many other factors that go into this such as more income could mean more hours worked and therefore less time for leisure and other factors affecting happiness score.

It is worth noting again that the income levels shown in the data is well above the United States poverty line by at least a facor of 3. The federal poverty line for the United States in 2020 is $ 12,760. The poverty line data is sourced from here

Does a higher unemployment rate mean a nation is less happy?¶

No strong correlation is observed between unemployment and the happiness score

Limitations¶

Only descriptive statistics was used throughout answering these questions and since no inferential statistics was used we cannot say our findings are correlation implying causation.

For our last 3 questions we have a signficantly smaller date range from 2005-2017 compared to the first 3 questions which have a data from as far back as 1800.

A few of the dataframes we used have null values which were filled in using the mean value for the dataset as shown in the process above.
